Below are pictures of a Mac 11 9mm, Cbrps bullpup SKS and a Mossberg500 tactical. If you email me or text Ill tell you all about them.
The Bullpup has had the most work put into her, It started of as a traditional SKS and modified heavily. I First took the clip off of it and modified it to accept extended magazines, I put in a new recoil spring (the old one was fine but I wanted to make sure it had a new one) . I decided to replace the receiver cover with a Texas Dog rail system and lighten the trigger. I also put on a short pin muzzle brake to reduce recoil...and because it makes it look bad ass when it shoots flames out the end. I then proceeded to put it in an Ati tactical stock with collapsible butt and added Knight's Armament Company rails to the front of the stock to "beefin" up the area in which I held the stock. I really liked the way it felt, very smooth shooter but when I seen the Cbrps Bullpup Stock I fell in love. I ordered it, put it on and shot it. I liked it but wanted the shell deflector taken off so I could leave the dog rail system on as a cheek rest.
Mac 11 9mm has some marks on her but shoots flawlessly,took it to shooters choice yesterday and shot a box through it without an issue. 

Mossberg 500 is a beauty, Ati adjustable stock with butt stock shell holder. Laser light combo and tru glo ghost ring sights on top. Put this together with a 18 1/2" barrel and you have a great home protection gun. 

Please do not ask me how much I will take. I want to trade. If you have nothing to trade, make a cash offer. Like most gentleman on here I do not like playing the back and forth price war so I respectfully ask for this question not to be asked.

postcontent:
Springfield Armory IMBEL SAR 4800 5.56 .223

This is a Springfield Armory SAR-4800. Chambered for 5.56 .223, this is the more "Politically Correct" version of the SAR-48, Springfield's version of the world famous FN FAL. Rare – very few imported in the 5.56mm caliber (.223), receiver is also marked 1005-SA-48-Match made by Imbel Brazil under FN contract, imported by Springfield Armory . It has the original thumbhole stock and "thread protector", two items that kept the rifle legal following the infamous assault rifle ban. This is a first class weapon, much better in quality and reliability than many pieced together FAL rifles. It features an adjustable gas operated semi-automatic action. Condition is excellent with only a very few minor handling marks. There is no rust or pitting. I'd grade this rifle at 98%+. Less than 100 rounds fired. The mechanics are in perfect working order and the bore is also excellent...bright with sharp rifling.

Comes in the original box and the following:
•	Three 30-round metal magazines with green followers

title: For Trade:  CUSTOM Glock 27 Gen. 4
postcontent: I have a custom Glock 27 Gen. 4 with a lot of modifications. It has a Zev Tech Fulcrum Trigger, with adjustable pre-travel and over travel, and can be adjusted from a 2 lb. trigger pull up to a 6 lb. trigger pull, and has 50% less trigger reset travel than stock. It's currently set up at 3.0 lbs. and average pre-travel for everyday carry. It has a Zev-Tech stainless steel polished skeletonized striker with a 4lb. Striker spring, and marine cups. It has a KKM Precision match grade barrel that was match fitted by KKM. It has a Tungsten Recoil double spring assembly that's 5x heavier than the factory polymer recoil assembly, and 2x heavier than a stainless recoil assembly. It really does reduce muzzle flip and recoil. It has a Zev Tech ejector housing with adjustable over travel, and a Lightning Strike polished titanium safety plunger with a reduced power safety plunger spring. It has a Ghost Evo 3.5 lb. connector with a 6lb. Trigger spring. Also has +1 Pearce Grip extensions on all 3 mags, and a Vickers Tactical Tango Down mag release, and slide catch. I also installed Trijicon night sights on it, and I have all the factory parts that I replaced to go with it. You can truly tell a huge difference in this gun and shooting a stock Glock. The mods aren't necessary, but are well worth the money if you want a nicer glock. If you are looking for a stock Glock this gun isn't for you. It's for the guy who wants a Glock that is heads and tails better than any other polymer frame pistol out there right now. It shoots amazingly, and has the best trigger of any gun I've shot that wasn't a $2,000.00 or more 1911, and I've shot them all. It's basically all the upgrades and match grade parts you find in a $2,000.00 1911, but in a Glock Platform. I'm just ready to move on, and build something else.

title: For Sale:  H-S Precision Pro Series  2000 .308 Winchester Tactical / Target Rifle
postcontent: This is a semi-custom HS Precision Pro Series 2000 Tactical / Target rifle in .308 Winchester. It has a 26 inch, cut -rifled, straight contour, 1.2 inch diameter at the muzzle bull barrel with a 1 in 12 twist. It's designed specifically to shoot 168 grain match ammo.  It might indeed handle 175 grainers but I've never shot them, but the specs ordered on chambering and twist were at the time, designed to optimize shooting 168 grainers.     Anyway, the barrel is actually stainless steel but has a Teflon-type exterior coating. I forgot the exact trade name HS Precision uses for it, but it's definitely a stainless barrel, not blued chrome moly. It has the HS Precision tactical stock in olive green with the aluminum bedding block.  Overall weight with scope is 15.5 pounds.   It has  a detachable muzzle break as well, which is a $ 220 added charge these days.  This rifle is essentially an earlier version of what they market these days as their  "HS Precision HTR (heavy tactical rifle)" with the only difference being that these days, they flute the barrel and ship them with detachable box magazines, whereas mine has an internal box magazine and is not fluted. But I'm an old school bench rest shooter, and so frankly, fluting looks cool, we all admit that,  but whether it really does add accuracy to the barrel is very much debatable. The last I'll say on this before I get hate mail from fluted barrel fans, is that  you don't really see many guys with fluted barrels shooting benchrest competitions...  Anyway, this rig shoots 1/2 MOA @ 100 yards all day long with Federal 168 grain match ammo and Hornady 168 grain match ammo, and I have shot many one-hole 3 shot groups with this thing.  Handloads have this shooting 1/4 MOA consistently and makes it a real competition worthy rig. As of now, I only have about 650-700 rounds through it, even though I've had it for years, which means it actually has several thousand rounds of good barrel life to it, and is still a very young barrel.  My only criticism of this rifle is the trigger, which is a bit rough and sticky for spoiled bench gun shooters like myself who get used to 2 ounce Jewell triggers on their bench guns. But for a tactical rifle in tactical applications where hair triggers are not appropriate, the trigger pull is correct, with slight stacking, probably measures out around 2.5 -3.25 pounds.  So if someone wanted to use this solely as a bench gun, it just takes some trigger work and you are there.  HS Precision charges about 3,600 for these rifles new these days, plus 220 for the muzzle break, then taxes and shipping, and you'd still have to wait at least 6 months to get one.  Mine is available at basically half that and can be had immediately.  Rifle can be sold with or without the Leupold scope, let me know what you want to do. It's a 6.5 x 20 x 50 on there right now.  And only reason I'm selling this is because I have a new, fully custom bench gun these days, and until I hit the Lotto, I just cant keep ALL my toys from days past:   sometimes things have  to go to pay for others, as much as it hurts .

title: For Sale:  KSG Kel-Tec
postcontent:
NEW! Never Fired! Mint Condition!

The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS

Caliber	12 gauge 3”
Barrel length	18.5"
Total capacity 
6+6+1
Weight empty	6.9lbs
Weight loaded	8.5lbs
Length	26.1"
Height	7"
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

The FNP-9’s barrel is cold hammer-forged stainless steel, and the stainless steel slide is available with a matte black industrial tool finish for added durability.
